03:08:48,560 --> 03:08:54,161
At eleven o'clock, Hercule Poirot 
called a meeting in the library.

2201
03:08:54,160 --> 03:08:58,439
'Please listen carefully to what I have to say.

2202
03:08:58,439 --> 03:09:05,399
I have been a friend for many years of Mr 
Entwhistle's and he was very upset by some words  

2203
03:09:05,399 --> 03:09:15,120
spoken on the day of Richard Abernethie's funeral 
by Mrs Lansquenet and asked me to investigate.'

2204
03:09:15,120 --> 03:09:17,359
No one spoke.

2205
03:09:17,359 --> 03:09:19,159
Poirot threw back his head.

2206
03:09:19,160 --> 03:09:24,680
'Eh hien, you will all be delighted 
to hear that as a result of my  

2207
03:09:24,680 --> 03:09:34,600
investigations - it is my belief that 
Mr Abernethie died a natural death.

2208
03:09:34,600 --> 03:09:38,720
That is good news, is it not?'

2209
03:09:38,720 --> 03:09:42,240
They stared at him and in all but the eyes of one  

2210
03:09:42,239 --> 03:09:47,479
person there still seemed 
to be doubt and suspicion.

2211
03:09:47,479 --> 03:09:51,559
The exception was Timothy Abernethie.

2212
03:09:51,560 --> 03:09:56,400
'Of course Richard wasn't 
murdered,' he said angrily.

2213
03:09:56,399 --> 03:09:59,279
'Well, Mr whatever your name is,  

2214
03:09:59,279 --> 03:10:05,639
I'm pleased you've had the sense to come to 
the right conclusion, though if you ask me,  

2215
03:10:05,640 --> 03:10:14,280
Entwhistle went far beyond his duty as Richard's 
lawyer to get you to come nosing about here.

2216
03:10:14,279 --> 03:10:17,359
If the family's satisfied...'

2217
03:10:17,359 --> 03:10:23,279
'But the family wasn't satisfied, 
Uncle Timothy,' said Rosamund.

2218
03:10:23,279 --> 03:10:26,840
'And what about Aunt Helen this morning?'

2219
03:10:26,840 --> 03:10:29,640
'Nonsense,' said Maude.

2220
03:10:29,640 --> 03:10:34,960
'Helen felt ill, came down and 
phoned the doctor, and then...'

2221
03:10:34,960 --> 03:10:39,120
'But she didn't phone the doctor,' said Rosamund.

2222
03:10:39,120 --> 03:10:41,880
'I asked him...'

2223
03:10:41,880 --> 03:10:46,680
Susan said sharply, 'Who did she phone?'

2224
03:10:46,680 --> 03:10:49,760
'I don't know,' said Rosamund.

2225
03:10:49,760 --> 03:10:54,720
'But I'm sure I can find out'

2226
03:10:54,720 --> 03:10:58,480
Hercule Poirot was sitting in the summerhouse.

2227
03:10:58,479 --> 03:11:03,399
He had told everyone that he was 
leaving on the twelve o'clock train.

2228
03:11:03,399 --> 03:11:06,879
There was still half an hour until then.

2229
03:11:06,880 --> 03:11:10,120
Half an hour for someone to come to him.

2230
03:11:10,120 --> 03:11:14,200
Perhaps more than one person.

2231
03:11:14,200 --> 03:11:21,040
He waited - like a cat waiting 
for a mouse to come out of hiding.

2232
03:11:21,040 --> 03:11:24,840
It was Miss Gilchrist who came first.

2233
03:11:24,840 --> 03:11:33,279
'Oh, Mr Pontarlier - I can't 
remember your other name,' she said.

2234
03:11:33,279 --> 03:11:39,679
'I had to come and speak to you, 
although I don't like doing it.

2235
03:11:39,680 --> 03:11:44,160
I did listen at the door that day 
Mr Richard Abernethie came to see  

2236
03:11:44,160 --> 03:11:52,479
his sister and he said something like, 
"There's no point in talking to Timothy.

2237
03:11:52,479 --> 03:11:54,639
He simply won't listen.

2238
03:11:54,640 --> 03:11:58,000
But I thought I'd like to tell you, Cora.

2239
03:11:58,000 --> 03:12:04,239
And though you've always liked to behave as if 
you are simple, you've got a lot of common sense.

2240
03:12:04,239 --> 03:12:09,760
So what would you do about it, if you were me?"

2241
03:12:09,760 --> 03:12:13,560
'I couldn't hear exactly what Mrs Lansquenet said,  

2242
03:12:13,560 --> 03:12:21,680
but I heard the word police - and then Mr 
Abernethie said loudly, "I can't do that.

2243
03:12:21,680 --> 03:12:27,320
Not when it's a question of my own 
niece." And then I had to run into  

2244
03:12:27,319 --> 03:12:34,960
the kitchen because something was burning, 
and when I got back Mr Abernethie was saying,  

2245
03:12:34,960 --> 03:12:40,720
"Even if I die an unnatural death, 
I don't want the police called in.

2246
03:12:40,720 --> 03:12:47,560
You understand that, don't you, my dear 
girl? But now that I know, I shall take  

2247
03:12:47,560 --> 03:12:53,240
all possible precautions." 
And then he said he'd made  

2248
03:12:53,239 --> 03:13:00,399
a mistake over her marriage because 
she had been happy with her husband.'

2249
03:13:00,399 --> 03:13:03,279
Miss Gilchrist stopped.

2250
03:13:03,279 --> 03:13:09,000
Poirot said, 'I see - I see...

2251
03:13:09,000 --> 03:13:14,520
Thank you, Miss Gilchrist, for coming to see me.'

2252
03:13:14,520 --> 03:13:20,081
Miss Gilchrist had no sooner 
gone before Gregory Banks came.

2253
03:13:20,080 --> 03:13:22,760
'At last!' he said.

2254
03:13:22,760 --> 03:13:26,320
'I thought that stupid woman would never go.

2255
03:13:26,319 --> 03:13:28,799
You're wrong about everything.

2256
03:13:28,800 --> 03:13:32,239
Richard Abernethie was killed.

2257
03:13:32,239 --> 03:13:35,679
I killed him.'

2258
03:13:35,680 --> 03:13:39,920
Hercule Poirot showed no surprise.

2259
03:13:39,920 --> 03:13:41,720
'How?'

2260
03:13:41,720 --> 03:13:44,360
Gregory Banks smiled.

2261
03:13:44,359 --> 03:13:47,160
'It wasn't difficult for me.

2262
03:13:47,160 --> 03:13:53,639
I worked out how I didn't need to be 
anywhere near Enderby at the time.'

2263
03:13:53,640 --> 03:13:57,201
'Clever,' said Poirot.

2264
03:13:57,200 --> 03:14:03,200
'Why did you kill him? For the 
money that would come to your wife?'

2265
03:14:03,200 --> 03:14:04,000
'No.

2266
03:14:04,000 --> 03:14:05,760
No, of course not.

2267
03:14:05,760 --> 03:14:09,120
I didn't marry Susan for her money!

2268
03:14:09,120 --> 03:14:12,279
Abernethie thought I was no good!

2269
03:14:12,279 --> 03:14:14,559
He sneered at me!

2270
03:14:14,560 --> 03:14:20,040
People can't do that to me and not be punished!'

2271
03:14:20,040 --> 03:14:24,840
'A most successful murder,' said Poirot.

2272
03:14:24,840 --> 03:14:29,800
'But why give yourself away - to me?'

2273
03:14:29,800 --> 03:14:32,760
'Because I had to show you 
that you're not as clever as  

2274
03:14:32,760 --> 03:14:40,080
you think you are - and besides - 
besides - It was wrong, wicked...

2275
03:14:40,080 --> 03:14:42,359
I must be punished...

2276
03:14:42,359 --> 03:14:47,040
I must go back there - to 
the place of punishment.!'

2277
03:14:48,640 --> 03:14:53,120
Poirot studied him for a moment or two.

2278
03:14:53,120 --> 03:14:59,160
'How badly do you want to 
get away from your wife?'

2279
03:14:59,160 --> 03:15:02,559
Gregory's face changed.

2280
03:15:02,560 --> 03:15:09,081
'Why couldn't she let me alone? 
She's coming now - across the lawn.

2281
03:15:09,080 --> 03:15:12,439
Tell her I've gone to the police station.

2282
03:15:12,439 --> 03:15:17,359
To confess.'

2283
03:15:17,359 --> 03:15:20,759
Susan came in breathlessly.

2284
03:15:20,760 --> 03:15:24,400
'Where's Greg? I saw him.'

2285
03:15:24,399 --> 03:15:25,160
'Yes.

2286
03:15:25,160 --> 03:15:31,319
He came to tell me that it was he 
who poisoned Richard Abernethie.'

2287
03:15:31,319 --> 03:15:33,559
'What absolute nonsense!

2288
03:15:33,560 --> 03:15:38,000
He wasn't even near this place 
when Uncle Richard died!'

2289
03:15:38,000 --> 03:15:40,279
'Perhaps not.

2290
03:15:40,279 --> 03:15:45,479
Where was he when Cora Lansquenet died?'

2291
03:15:45,479 --> 03:15:46,759
'In London.

2292
03:15:46,760 --> 03:15:49,160
We both were.'

2293
03:15:49,160 --> 03:15:52,239
Hercule Poirot shook his head.

2294
03:15:52,239 --> 03:15:53,920
'No, no.

2295
03:15:53,920 --> 03:15:56,600
You went to Lytchett St Mary.

2296
03:15:56,600 --> 03:16:02,960
My inquiries say that you were there 
on the afternoon Cora Lansquenet died.

2297
03:16:02,960 --> 03:16:08,800
You parked your car in the same quarry where 
you left it the morning of the inquest.

2298
03:16:08,800 --> 03:16:14,920
The car was seen and the number was noted.'

2299
03:16:14,920 --> 03:16:16,920
Susan stared at him.

2300
03:16:17,479 --> 03:16:19,000
'All right.

2301
03:16:19,000 --> 03:16:22,399
What Cora said at the funeral worried me.

2302
03:16:22,399 --> 03:16:28,759
I decided to go and see her, and ask 
her what had put the idea into her head.

2303
03:16:28,760 --> 03:16:35,960
I got there about three o'clock, knocked 
and rang, but there was no answer.

2304
03:16:35,960 --> 03:16:39,279
I didn't go round to the back of the cottage.

2305
03:16:39,279 --> 03:16:43,319
If I had, I might have seen the broken window.

2306
03:16:43,319 --> 03:16:50,239
I went back to London without any 
idea there was anything wrong.'

2307
03:16:50,239 --> 03:16:55,639
'I know something of your 
husband's history,' said Poirot.

2308
03:16:55,640 --> 03:17:00,120
'He has a punishment complex.'

2309
03:17:00,120 --> 03:17:02,960
'You don't understand, Monsieur Poirot.

2310
03:17:02,960 --> 03:17:06,880
Greg has never had a chance in life.

2311
03:17:06,880 --> 03:17:10,760
That's why I wanted Uncle 
Richard's money so badly.

2312
03:17:10,760 --> 03:17:15,080
I knew Greg needed to feel he was someone.

2313
03:17:15,080 --> 03:17:16,840
Everything will be different now.

2314
03:17:17,560 --> 03:17:19,960
He will have his own laboratory.

2315
03:17:19,960 --> 03:17:24,160
No one will tell him what to do.'

2316
03:17:24,160 --> 03:17:29,000
'Yes, yes - you will give him everything - but you  

2317
03:17:29,000 --> 03:17:34,359
cannot give to people what they 
are not capable of receiving.

2318
03:17:34,359 --> 03:17:42,519
At the end of it all, he will still be 
something that he does not want to be.'

2319
03:17:42,520 --> 03:17:44,760
'What's that?'

2320
03:17:44,760 --> 03:17:46,840
'Susan's husband.

2321
03:17:48,359 --> 03:17:55,239
Where Gregory Banks is concerned 
you have no sense of right or wrong.

2322
03:17:55,239 --> 03:17:58,800
You wanted your uncle's money - for your husband.

2323
03:17:58,800 --> 03:18:02,920
How badly did you want it?'

2324
03:18:02,920 --> 03:18:09,080
Angrily, Susan turned and ran away.

2325
03:18:09,080 --> 03:18:15,880
'I thought,' said Michael Shane, 
'that I'd just come and say goodbye.'

2326
03:18:15,880 --> 03:18:23,920
'Your wife Rosamund,' said 
Poirot, 'is a very unusual woman.'

2327
03:18:23,920 --> 03:18:26,440
Michael raised his eyebrows.

2328
03:18:26,439 --> 03:18:28,639
'She's lovely, I agree.

2329
03:18:28,640 --> 03:18:32,760
But she's not known for her intelligence.'

2330
03:18:32,760 --> 03:18:37,560
'She will never be clever,' Poirot agreed.

2331
03:18:37,560 --> 03:18:43,000
'But she knows what she wants.' He sighed.

2332
03:18:43,760 --> 03:18:52,440
'So few people do.' Poirot placed 
the tips of his fingers together.

2333
03:18:52,439 --> 03:18:55,719
'There have been inquiries made, you know.

2334
03:18:55,720 --> 03:18:59,120
Not only by me.'

2335
03:18:59,120 --> 03:19:06,599
'You mean - the police are interested? And 
they've been making inquiries about me?'

2336
03:19:06,600 --> 03:19:11,720
Poirot said quietly, 'They are 
interested in the movements of  

2337
03:19:11,720 --> 03:19:16,720
Mrs Lansquenet's relations on 
the day that she was killed.'

2338
03:19:17,960 --> 03:19:20,120
'That's extremely awkward.

2339
03:19:20,120 --> 03:19:25,359
I told Rosamund that I was having 
lunch with Oscar Lewis on that day.

2340
03:19:25,359 --> 03:19:31,359
Actually I went to see a woman called 
Sorrel Dainton - and though that's  

2341
03:19:31,359 --> 03:19:38,719
satisfactory as far as the police are 
concerned, Rosamund won't be pleased.'

2342
03:19:38,720 --> 03:19:46,720
'I see - I see - and this Miss 
Dainton, she will confirm your alibi?'

2343
03:19:46,720 --> 03:19:50,280
'She won't like it - but she'll do it.'

2344
03:19:50,279 --> 03:19:57,479
'She would do it, perhaps, even if you 
were not having an affair with her.'

2345
03:19:57,479 --> 03:19:59,160
'What do you mean?'

2346
03:19:59,160 --> 03:20:01,720
'The lady is in love with you.

2347
03:20:01,720 --> 03:20:11,080
When they are in love, women will swear to 
what is true - and also to what is untrue.'

2348
03:20:11,080 --> 03:20:14,319
'Do you mean to say that you don't believe me?'

2349
03:20:14,319 --> 03:20:18,559
'It does not matter if I believe you or not.

2350
03:20:18,560 --> 03:20:23,560
It is not me you have to satisfy.'

2351
03:20:23,560 --> 03:20:25,440
'Who then?'

2352
03:20:25,439 --> 03:20:27,719
Poirot smiled.

2353
03:20:27,720 --> 03:20:35,640
'Inspector Morton - who has just 
come out through the side door.'

2354
03:20:35,640 --> 03:20:40,880
Michael Shane turned round quickly.

2355
03:20:40,880 --> 03:20:43,920
CHAPTER TWENTY ONE

2356
03:20:43,920 --> 03:20:50,359
'I heard you were here, Monsieur Poirot,' 
said Inspector Morton when they were alone.

2357
03:20:50,359 --> 03:20:54,319
'I came over with Superintendent Parwell.

2358
03:20:54,319 --> 03:21:02,199
Dr Larraby phoned him about Mrs Helen 
Abernethie and he's come over to make inquiries.

2359
03:21:02,199 --> 03:21:08,000
I wanted to ask a few questions - and 
the people I wanted to ask seemed,  

2360
03:21:08,000 --> 03:21:12,199
very conveniently, to be all here.

2361
03:21:12,199 --> 03:21:14,920
Did you do that?'

2362
03:21:14,920 --> 03:21:16,560
'Yes, I did.'

2363
03:21:17,199 --> 03:21:23,559
'And as a result someone hit Mrs 
Helen Abernethie on the head.'

2364
03:21:23,560 --> 03:21:26,200
'You must not blame me for that.

2365
03:21:26,199 --> 03:21:29,040
If she had come to me...

2366
03:21:29,040 --> 03:21:31,000
But she did not.

2367
03:21:31,000 --> 03:21:34,399
Instead she called her lawyer in London.

2368
03:21:34,399 --> 03:21:39,679
Now, I will ask you, my friend, 
to give me a few more hours,  

2369
03:21:39,680 --> 03:21:45,600
then I may be able to hand you 
a piece of solid evidence.'

2370
03:21:45,600 --> 03:21:49,760
'We certainly need it,' said Inspector Morton.

2371
03:21:49,760 --> 03:21:54,239
'Though we have our found out that 
two nuns were out collecting money  

2372
03:21:54,239 --> 03:22:00,319
and went to Mrs Lansquenet's cottage 
on the day before she was murdered.

2373
03:22:00,319 --> 03:22:04,040
No one answered when they knocked and rang - Mrs  

2374
03:22:04,040 --> 03:22:11,040
Lansquenet was at the Abernethie funeral 
and Gilchrist had gone out for the day.

2375
03:22:11,040 --> 03:22:19,080
The point is that they say they heard 
sighs and groans from inside the cottage.

2376
03:22:19,080 --> 03:22:29,760
So was there someone there? And if so, who? 
All the Abernethie family were at the funeral.'

2377
03:22:29,760 --> 03:22:36,080
'These nuns, did they return 
at a later date to try again?'

2378
03:22:36,080 --> 03:22:40,880
'Actually, they did - on the day of the inquest.'

2379
03:22:40,880 --> 03:22:45,359
'That fits,' said Hercule Poirot.

2380
03:22:45,359 --> 03:22:50,160
'You will have noticed, Inspector, 
that the visit of the nuns was the  

2381
03:22:50,160 --> 03:22:56,760
same day that poisoned wedding cake 
found its way into that cottage.'

2382
03:22:56,760 --> 03:22:59,880
'That's a ridiculous idea!'

2383
03:22:59,880 --> 03:23:06,120
'My ideas are never ridiculous,' 
said Hercule Poirot.

2384
03:23:06,120 --> 03:23:14,880
'And now, mon cher, I must go in search 
of the late Richard Abernethie's niece.'

2385
03:23:14,880 --> 03:23:18,920
'Now be careful what you say to Mrs Banks.'

2386
03:23:18,920 --> 03:23:21,680
'I do not mean Mrs Banks.

2387
03:23:21,680 --> 03:23:28,080
I mean Richard Abernethie's other niece.'

2388
03:23:28,080 --> 03:23:33,239
Poirot found Rosamund sitting 
on a bench by a little pool.

2389
03:23:33,239 --> 03:23:36,080
'I thought you'd gone,' she said.

2390
03:23:36,080 --> 03:23:39,080
'It's past twelve o'clock.'

2391
03:23:39,080 --> 03:23:43,600
'I have missed my train,' said Poirot.

2392
03:23:43,600 --> 03:23:48,121
'Do you know, Madame, I have been 
sitting in the little summerhouse  

2393
03:23:48,120 --> 03:23:53,319
hoping that you would, perhaps, visit me there?'

2394
03:23:53,319 --> 03:23:57,319
'Why should I? I had a lot to think about.

2395
03:23:57,319 --> 03:24:01,799
I don't often do much thinking 
- it seems a waste of time.

2396
03:24:01,800 --> 03:24:04,360
But this is important.

2397
03:24:04,359 --> 03:24:10,239
I think one ought to plan one's 
life just as one wants it to be.'

2398
03:24:10,239 --> 03:24:13,679
'And that is what you are doing?'

2399
03:24:13,680 --> 03:24:15,400
'Well, yes...

2400
03:24:15,399 --> 03:24:19,199
I was trying to make a decision about something.'

2401
03:24:19,199 --> 03:24:21,720
'About your husband?'

2402
03:24:21,720 --> 03:24:24,520
'In a way.'

2403
03:24:24,520 --> 03:24:31,520
Poirot waited a moment, then he said, 
'Inspector Morton has just arrived.

2404
03:24:31,520 --> 03:24:34,880
He has come to get statements from you all about  

2405
03:24:34,880 --> 03:24:40,640
what you were doing on the day 
Cora Lansquenet was murdered.'

2406
03:24:40,640 --> 03:24:41,800
'I see.

2407
03:24:41,800 --> 03:24:45,840
Alibis' said Rosamund cheerfully.

2408
03:24:45,840 --> 03:24:48,080
'That will be hell for Michael.

2409
03:24:48,080 --> 03:24:52,960
He thinks I don't know he 
spent the day with that woman.'

2410
03:24:52,960 --> 03:24:55,760
'How did you know?'

2411
03:24:55,760 --> 03:25:00,080
'It was obvious from the way he said 
he was going to lunch with Oscar,  

2412
03:25:00,080 --> 03:25:06,120
and his face always does something 
strange when he tells lies.'

2413
03:25:06,120 --> 03:25:11,559
'How thankful I am I am 
not married to you, Madame!

2414
03:25:11,560 --> 03:25:20,081
He is not, I fear, a very faithful 
husband?' Poirot suggested.

2415
03:25:20,080 --> 03:25:22,160
'No.'

2416
03:25:22,160 --> 03:25:25,199
'But you do not mind?'

2417
03:25:25,199 --> 03:25:32,279
'Well, it's fun having a husband that all 
the other women want to steal from you.'

2418
03:25:32,279 --> 03:25:35,239
Poirot was studying her.

2419
03:25:35,239 --> 03:25:42,719
'And suppose someone did succeed - in 
stealing your husband away from you?'

2420
03:25:42,720 --> 03:25:45,600
'They won't,' said Rosamund.

2421
03:25:45,600 --> 03:25:48,840
'Not now that there's Uncle Richard's money.

2422
03:25:48,840 --> 03:25:51,440
He can finance his own shows.

2423
03:25:51,439 --> 03:25:53,679
And he really is good.

2424
03:25:53,680 --> 03:25:55,360
Not like me.

2425
03:25:55,359 --> 03:26:01,000
I love acting - but I'm terrible 
at it, though I do look nice.

2426
03:26:01,000 --> 03:26:05,199
No, I'm not worried about Michael any more.

2427
03:26:05,199 --> 03:26:09,800
Because it's my money, you see.'

2428
03:26:09,800 --> 03:26:13,080
Her eyes met Poirot's.

2429
03:26:13,080 --> 03:26:21,760
'I think, Madame, that you must allow your 
cousin Susan to have the green marble table.'

2430
03:26:21,760 --> 03:26:25,520
Rosamund's eyes opened very wide.

2431
03:26:25,520 --> 03:26:29,240
'Why should I? I want it.'

2432
03:26:29,239 --> 03:26:30,399
'I know.

2433
03:26:30,399 --> 03:26:35,279
But you - you will keep your husband.

2434
03:26:35,279 --> 03:26:42,040
And poor Susan, she will lose hers.'
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

2435
03:26:42,040 --> 03:26:44,960
CHAPTER TWENTY TWO

2436
03:26:44,960 --> 03:26:48,800
The telegram came about six o'clock that evening,  

2437
03:26:48,800 --> 03:26:54,840
and then Hercule Poirot gathered 
his audience and began speaking.

2438
03:26:54,840 --> 03:26:57,600
'The puzzle is solved.

2439
03:26:57,600 --> 03:27:01,560
Let me first, go over the various 
points which were brought to my  

2440
03:27:01,560 --> 03:27:06,200
attention by the excellent Mr Entwhistle.

2441
03:27:06,199 --> 03:27:11,800
'First, Mr Richard Abernethie dies suddenly.

2442
03:27:11,800 --> 03:27:19,600
Secondly, after his funeral, his sister 
Cora Lansquenet says, "He was murdered,  

2443
03:27:19,600 --> 03:27:26,200
wasn't he?" Thirdly Mrs Lansquenet is killed.

2444
03:27:26,199 --> 03:27:31,279
Then Miss Gilchrist becomes ill 
after eating a piece of wedding cake,  

2445
03:27:31,279 --> 03:27:34,960
which was poisoned with arsenic.

2446
03:27:34,960 --> 03:27:39,800
That is the next step in the sequence.

2447
03:27:39,800 --> 03:27:44,960
'I have found nothing to prove 
that Mr Abernethie was poisoned.

2448
03:27:44,960 --> 03:27:50,520
Equally, I have found nothing 
to prove that he was not.

2449
03:27:50,520 --> 03:27:57,520
But Cora Lansquenet undoubtedly 
asked that shocking question.

2450
03:27:57,520 --> 03:28:01,081
And undoubtedly Mrs Lansquenet was murdered.

2451
03:28:01,080 --> 03:28:08,160
Now, the post van driver strongly believes 
that he did not deliver that wedding cake.

2452
03:28:08,160 --> 03:28:16,319
If that is so, then the parcel was left by 
hand and though we cannot exclude a "person  

2453
03:28:16,319 --> 03:28:24,880
unknown" - we must consider those people who 
were able to put the parcel where it was found.

2454
03:28:24,880 --> 03:28:32,600
Those were: Miss Gilchrist herself, of 
course; Susan Banks; Mr Entwhistle and  

2455
03:28:32,600 --> 03:28:43,600
Mr Guthrie, an art critic; and a nun 
or nuns who called to collect money.

2456
03:28:43,600 --> 03:28:50,200
'Miss Gilchrist did not benefit by Richard 
Abernethie's death and in only a very small way by  

2457
03:28:50,199 --> 03:28:59,559
the death of Mrs Lansquenet - and Miss Gilchrist 
was taken to hospital with arsenic poisoning.

2458
03:28:59,560 --> 03:29:08,920
'Susan Banks did benefit from Richard Abernethie's 
death, and in a small way from Mrs Lansquenet's.

2459
03:29:08,920 --> 03:29:12,760
She might have believed that 
Miss Gilchrist had overheard  

2460
03:29:12,760 --> 03:29:20,120
a conversation between Cora Lansquenet and 
Richard Abernethie which referred to her.

2461
03:29:20,120 --> 03:29:27,519
Because of that she might have decided 
that Miss Gilchrist must be killed.

2462
03:29:27,520 --> 03:29:34,240
She did, after all, refuse 
to eat the wedding cake.

2463
03:29:34,239 --> 03:29:41,399
'Mr Entwhistle did not benefit by either of 
the deaths - but he did have considerable  

2464
03:29:41,399 --> 03:29:46,359
control over Mr Abernethie's affairs, 
and there could easily be some reason  

2465
03:29:46,359 --> 03:29:51,759
why Richard Abernethie should not live too long.

2466
03:29:51,760 --> 03:30:01,160
But - you will say - if it is Mr Entwhistle 
who was worried, why should he come to me?

2467
03:30:01,160 --> 03:30:12,680
And that I will answer - it is not the first time 
that a murderer has been too sure of himself.

2468
03:30:12,680 --> 03:30:15,360
'We now come to Mr Guthrie.

2469
03:30:15,359 --> 03:30:21,319
If Mr Guthrie is really Mr Guthrie, 
the art critic, then that clears him.

2470
03:30:21,319 --> 03:30:25,960
The same is true for the 
nun, if she is really a nun.

2471
03:30:25,960 --> 03:30:35,399
The question is: are these people 
themselves, or are they somebody else?

2472
03:30:35,399 --> 03:30:39,120
'And there seems to be a strange - pattern - one  

2473
03:30:39,120 --> 03:30:44,920
might call it - of a nun 
all through this business.

2474
03:30:44,920 --> 03:30:49,720
A nun comes to the door of Mr Timothy 
Abernethie's house and Miss Gilchrist  

2475
03:30:49,720 --> 03:30:54,080
believes it is the same nun 
she has seen at Cora's house.

2476
03:30:54,080 --> 03:31:02,760
Also a nun, or nuns, called here 
the day before Mr Abernethie died.

2477
03:31:02,760 --> 03:31:10,120
'Other features of the case caught my attention: 
the visit of an art critic, a smell of oil paint,  

2478
03:31:10,120 --> 03:31:21,160
a picture postcard of Polflexan harbour, 
and finally a bouquet of wax flowers.

2479
03:31:21,160 --> 03:31:27,239
'It was thinking about these 
things that led me to the truth.

2480
03:31:27,239 --> 03:31:33,199
Richard Abernethie died suddenly - but 
there would have been no reason to suspect  

2481
03:31:33,199 --> 03:31:39,679
murder if it had not been for the words 
said by his sister Cora at his funeral.

2482
03:31:39,680 --> 03:31:43,760
You all believed them because Cora Lansquenet had  

2483
03:31:43,760 --> 03:31:49,880
always been famous for speaking 
the truth at difficult moments.

2484
03:31:49,880 --> 03:31:57,600
'And now I come to the question 
that I suddenly asked myself:  

2485
03:31:57,600 --> 03:32:09,360
How well did you all know Cora Lansquenet? 
And Not well at all is the answer!

2486
03:32:09,359 --> 03:32:16,120
There were actually only three people 
present that day who really knew Cora.

2487
03:32:16,120 --> 03:32:22,920
Lanscombe, the butler, who is old and 
almost blind; Mrs Maude Abernethie  

2488
03:32:22,920 --> 03:32:28,640
who had only seen her a few times round 
about the date of her own wedding; and

2489
03:32:28,640 --> 03:32:35,480
Mrs Helen Abernethie who had not 
seen her for over thirty years.

2490
03:32:35,479 --> 03:32:45,839
'So I said to myself: "Supposing it was not Cora 
Lansquenet who came to the funeral that day?'"

2491
03:32:46,920 --> 03:32:53,960
'Do you mean that it wasn't Aunt Cora who was 
murdered, but someone else?' Susan demanded.

2492
03:32:53,960 --> 03:32:59,080
'No, no, it was Cora Lansquenet who was murdered.

2493
03:32:59,080 --> 03:33:06,239
But it was not Cora Lansquenet 
who came to the funeral.

2494
03:33:06,239 --> 03:33:11,399
The woman who came that day came for 
one purpose only - to create in the  

2495
03:33:11,399 --> 03:33:19,960
minds of his relations the idea that 
Richard Abernethie had been murdered!'

2496
03:33:19,960 --> 03:33:25,080
'Why? What was the point of it?' Maude asked.

2497
03:33:25,080 --> 03:33:34,160
'To draw attention away from the murder of 
Cora Lansquenet herself For if Cora says  

2498
03:33:34,160 --> 03:33:38,800
that Richard has been murdered, and 
the next day she herself is killed,  

2499
03:33:38,800 --> 03:33:44,720
then her death will be believed 
to be the result of what she said.

2500
03:33:44,720 --> 03:33:52,080
But if Cora had simply been murdered without 
making her comment about Richard's death,  

2501
03:33:52,080 --> 03:33:57,080
and if the "robbery" did not convince the police,  

2502
03:33:57,080 --> 03:34:05,960
then suspicion would be likely to fall on 
the woman who shared the house with her.'

2503
03:34:05,960 --> 03:34:11,520
Miss Gilchrist protested, 'Oh really, 
you don't suggest I'd commit a murder  

2504
03:34:11,520 --> 03:34:15,720
for a piece of jewellery and 
a few worthless watercolours?'

2505
03:34:17,560 --> 03:34:20,560
'No,' said Poirot.

2506
03:34:20,560 --> 03:34:28,320
'But one of those watercolours represented 
Polflexan harbour which, as Mrs Banks realized,  

2507
03:34:28,319 --> 03:34:35,960
had been copied from a picture postcard 
which showed the old pier still in position.

2508
03:34:35,960 --> 03:34:42,520
Yet Mrs Lansquenet painted always from life.

2509
03:34:42,520 --> 03:34:50,480
Mr Entwhistle had mentioned there being 
a smell of oil paint in the cottage.

2510
03:34:50,479 --> 03:35:01,759
You can paint, can't you, Miss Gilchrist? And 
you had been painting over another picture.

2511
03:35:01,760 --> 03:35:04,560
You know a lot about painting.

2512
03:35:04,560 --> 03:35:14,121
Supposing that one of the pictures that Cora 
bought at a sale was a really valuable one.

2513
03:35:14,120 --> 03:35:22,160
Supposing that she did not 
recognize it, but that you did.

2514
03:35:22,160 --> 03:35:27,639
You knew she was expecting a visit 
from a well-known art critic.

2515
03:35:27,640 --> 03:35:35,560
Then her brother died suddenly - 
and a plan comes into your head.

2516
03:35:35,560 --> 03:35:41,280
It was easy to put a sleeping drug in her 
morning tea that would keep her unconscious  

2517
03:35:41,279 --> 03:35:48,840
for the whole of the day of the funeral 
whilst you played her part at Enderby.

2518
03:35:48,840 --> 03:35:51,840
She talked a lot about her 
childhood days so it was  

2519
03:35:51,840 --> 03:35:57,840
easy for you to "remember" incidents and objects.

2520
03:35:57,840 --> 03:36:05,480
You were wearing Cora's clothes, with padding 
to make you look larger, and a false fringe.

2521
03:36:05,479 --> 03:36:14,719
And Cora had certain mannerisms, all of which 
you had practised carefully before a mirror.

2522
03:36:14,720 --> 03:36:24,480
'But you forgot that a mirror image is reversed.

2523
03:36:24,479 --> 03:36:30,399
When you saw in the glass the perfect 
reproduction of Cora's sideways movement  

2524
03:36:30,399 --> 03:36:40,679
of the head, you didn't realize that 
it was actually the wrong way round.

2525
03:36:40,680 --> 03:36:44,000
You saw Cora tilting her head to the right - but  

2526
03:36:44,000 --> 03:36:51,319
your own head was tilted to the left 
to produce that effect in the mirror.

2527
03:36:51,319 --> 03:36:59,479
'That was what puzzled Helen Abernethie at the 
moment when you asked your famous question.

2528
03:36:59,479 --> 03:37:04,359
Something seemed to her "wrong".

2529
03:37:04,359 --> 03:37:07,719
I realized myself the other 
night when Rosamund Shane  

2530
03:37:07,720 --> 03:37:14,240
made an unexpected comment about 
what happens on such an occasion.

2531
03:37:14,239 --> 03:37:18,080
Everybody looks at the speaker.

2532
03:37:18,080 --> 03:37:26,640
After the talk about mirror images, I think 
Helen Abernethie experimented before her mirror.

2533
03:37:26,640 --> 03:37:32,600
She probably thought of Cora, remembered 
how Cora used to tilt her head to the right,  

2534
03:37:32,600 --> 03:37:36,280
did so, and looked in the 
mirror - when, of course,  

2535
03:37:36,279 --> 03:37:42,759
she realized just what had been 
wrong on the day of the funeral.

2536
03:37:42,760 --> 03:37:49,320
She was determined to tell Mr Entwhistle of 
her discovery as soon as she woke next morning.

2537
03:37:49,319 --> 03:37:59,799
But someone who was used to getting up early 
followed her downstairs and hit her on the head.

2538
03:37:59,800 --> 03:38:07,520
'I may as well tell you now that 
Mrs Abernethie is not seriously ill.

2539
03:38:07,520 --> 03:38:12,000
She will soon be able to tell us her own story.

2540
03:38:12,000 --> 03:38:15,800
That aside, at any moment you 
were prepared to admit that you  

2541
03:38:15,800 --> 03:38:19,480
had listened to a conversation 
between Richard and his sister.

2542
03:38:19,479 --> 03:38:26,679
What he actually told her, no doubt, was 
the fact that he had not long to live,  

2543
03:38:26,680 --> 03:38:34,120
and that explains a phrase in the letter 
he wrote to her after getting home.

2544
03:38:34,120 --> 03:38:39,080
The "nun" was another of your suggestions.

2545
03:38:39,080 --> 03:38:43,640
The nuns who called at the cottage on 
the day of the inquest suggested to you  

2546
03:38:43,640 --> 03:38:49,880
a mention of a nun who was "following 
you round", and you used that when you  

2547
03:38:49,880 --> 03:38:57,359
were anxious to hear what Maude Abernethie 
was saying to her sister-in-law at Enderby.

2548
03:38:57,359 --> 03:39:02,399
And also because you wished to 
go with her there and find out  

2549
03:39:02,399 --> 03:39:07,559
for yourself just what suspicions there were.

2550
03:39:07,560 --> 03:39:13,161
To poison yourself, badly but not fatally,  

2551
03:39:13,160 --> 03:39:22,680
with arsenic, is a very old trick- and 
made Inspector Morton suspicious of you.'

2552
03:39:22,680 --> 03:39:25,800
'But the picture?' said Rosamund.

2553
03:39:25,800 --> 03:39:28,520
'What was it?'

2554
03:39:28,520 --> 03:39:33,240
Poirot slowly unfolded a telegram.

2555
03:39:33,239 --> 03:39:39,080
'This morning Mr Entwhistle went 
to Mr Timothy Abernethie's house  

2556
03:39:39,080 --> 03:39:44,199
to look among the pictures 
in Miss Gilchrist's room.

2557
03:39:44,199 --> 03:39:45,639
He was to take the one  

2558
03:39:45,640 --> 03:39:54,800
of Polflexan Harbour to London and go to Mr 
Guthrie whom I had contacted by telegram.

2559
03:39:54,800 --> 03:39:59,320
The hastily painted sketch of 
Polflexan was removed from the  

2560
03:39:59,319 --> 03:40:07,399
surface and the original picture was exposed.'

2561
03:40:07,399 --> 03:40:11,679
He held up the telegram and read:

2562
03:40:11,680 --> 03:40:15,760
'Definitely a Vermeer.

2563
03:40:15,760 --> 03:40:20,400
Guthrie.'

2564
03:40:20,399 --> 03:40:23,879
Suddenly, Miss Gilchrist spoke.

2565
03:40:23,880 --> 03:40:25,960
'I knew it was a Vermeer.

2566
03:40:25,960 --> 03:40:27,840
She didn't know!

2567
03:40:27,840 --> 03:40:34,120
She was always talking about Enderby, 
and what they did there as children.

2568
03:40:34,120 --> 03:40:38,800
You don't know how boring it is, 
listening to somebody saying the  

2569
03:40:38,800 --> 03:40:45,320
same things, hour after hour and day after day.

2570
03:40:45,319 --> 03:40:49,279
Boring - boring - boring.

2571
03:40:49,279 --> 03:40:52,639
And nothing to look forward to.

2572
03:40:52,640 --> 03:40:56,840
And then - a Vermeer!

2573
03:40:56,840 --> 03:41:04,040
Another Vermeer sold recently 
for over five thousand pounds!'

2574
03:41:04,040 --> 03:41:12,560
'You killed her for five thousand 
pounds?' Susan's voice was shocked.

2575
03:41:12,560 --> 03:41:19,380
'Five thousand pounds,' said Poirot, 
'would have paid for a tearoom...'

2576
03:41:20,600 --> 03:41:25,840
'At least,' Miss Gilchrist said, 'you understand.

2577
03:41:25,840 --> 03:41:29,279
I was going to call it the Palm Tree.

2578
03:41:29,279 --> 03:41:38,479
And have wooden tables - and little chairs 
with striped red and white cushions...'

2579
03:41:38,479 --> 03:41:42,519
For a few moments, the 
tearoom that would never be,  

2580
03:41:42,520 --> 03:41:45,240
seemed more real than the sitting room at Enderby.

2581
03:41:47,159 --> 03:41:54,120
It was Inspector Morton who broke the silence 
by asking Miss Gilchrist to go with him.

2582
03:41:54,120 --> 03:41:57,319
'Oh, certainly,' she said.

2583
03:41:57,319 --> 03:42:00,120
'I don't want to give any trouble.

2584
03:42:00,120 --> 03:42:10,760
After all, if I can't have the Palm Tree, 
nothing really seems to matter very much...'

2585
03:42:10,760 --> 03:42:15,400
She went out of the room with 
him and Susan said, her voice  

2586
03:42:15,399 --> 03:42:22,519
still shaken, 'I've never 
imagined a ladylike murderer.

2587
03:42:22,520 --> 03:42:26,121
It's horrible...'
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

2588
03:42:26,120 --> 03:42:29,319
CHAPTER TWENTY THREE

2589
03:42:29,319 --> 03:42:37,359
'But I don't understand the connection between the 
wax flowers and the marble table,' said Rosamund.

2590
03:42:37,359 --> 03:42:43,920
They were at Helen's flat and Rosamund 
and Poirot were having tea with her.

2591
03:42:43,920 --> 03:42:45,120
'The table, no.

2592
03:42:46,279 --> 03:42:54,239
But Miss Gilchrist said how nice the wax 
flowers looked on the green marble table.

2593
03:42:54,239 --> 03:42:57,439
And she could not have seen them there.

2594
03:42:57,439 --> 03:43:02,399
Because they had been broken 
and put away before she arrived.

2595
03:43:02,399 --> 03:43:11,199
So she could only have seen them when 
she was there as Cora Lansquenet.'

2596
03:43:11,199 --> 03:43:15,120
'That was stupid of her, 
wasn't it?' said Rosamund.

2597
03:43:16,479 --> 03:43:19,559
Poirot shook a finger at her.

2598
03:43:19,560 --> 03:43:25,600
'It shows you, Madame, the 
dangers of conversations.

2599
03:43:25,600 --> 03:43:32,160
It is a strong belief of mine that if you can 
get a person to talk to you for long enough,  

2600
03:43:32,159 --> 03:43:41,800
on any subject whatever - sooner or 
later they will give themselves away.

2601
03:43:41,800 --> 03:43:45,120
Miss Gilchrist did.'

2602
03:43:45,120 --> 03:43:50,040
'I shall have to be careful,' 
said Rosamund thoughtfully.

2603
03:43:50,040 --> 03:43:53,840
'Did you know? I'm going to have a baby.

2604
03:43:53,840 --> 03:43:58,640
And I've decided to leave the 
stage and just be a mother.

2605
03:43:58,640 --> 03:44:01,280
Michael is delighted.

2606
03:44:01,279 --> 03:44:03,960
I didn't really think he would be.

2607
03:44:03,960 --> 03:44:07,199
So Susan's got the marble table.

2608
03:44:07,199 --> 03:44:11,279
I thought, as I was having a baby...'

2609
03:44:11,279 --> 03:44:15,159
She left the sentence unfinished.

2610
03:44:15,159 --> 03:44:22,519
'I think Susan is going to have a big success 
with her beauty business,' said Helen.

2611
03:44:22,520 --> 03:44:29,400
'Yes, she was born to succeed,' said Poirot.

2612
03:44:29,399 --> 03:44:33,359
'Greg's gone away somewhere,' said Rosamund.

2613
03:44:33,359 --> 03:44:37,719
'He's having a rest cure, Susan says.'

2614
03:44:37,720 --> 03:44:40,800
Poirot turned to Helen.

2615
03:44:40,800 --> 03:44:45,040
'And you, Madame, are off to Cyprus?'

2616
03:44:45,760 --> 03:44:48,880
'Yes, in two weeks.'

2617
03:44:48,880 --> 03:44:53,880
'Then let me wish you a happy journey.'

2618
03:44:53,880 --> 03:44:59,600
She went with him to the door, 
and said, 'Monsieur Poirot,  

2619
03:44:59,600 --> 03:45:07,040
the income Richard left me meant more to 
me than theirs did to any of the others.

2620
03:45:07,040 --> 03:45:12,720
You see - there is a child in Cyprus...

2621
03:45:12,720 --> 03:45:18,640
After my husband died, my 
loneliness was unbelievable  

2622
03:45:18,640 --> 03:45:25,480
and when I was nursing in London at 
the end of the war, I met someone...

2623
03:45:25,479 --> 03:45:34,679
We lived together for a little while, then he went 
back to Canada - to his wife and his children.

2624
03:45:34,680 --> 03:45:39,600
He never knew about - our child.

2625
03:45:39,600 --> 03:45:47,920
It seemed like a miracle to me - a middle-aged 
woman with everything seemingly behind her.

2626
03:45:47,920 --> 03:45:54,640
Now, with Richard's money, I can send 
my "nephew" to an even better school,  

2627
03:45:54,640 --> 03:45:58,440
and give him a start in life.

2628
03:45:58,439 --> 03:46:01,080
I never told Richard.

2629
03:46:01,080 --> 03:46:06,479
He was fond of me - but he 
would not have understood.

2630
03:46:06,479 --> 03:46:11,679
I wanted you to know this about me.'

2631
03:46:11,680 --> 03:46:14,920
Poirot bowed over her hand.

2632
03:46:16,239 --> 03:46:22,040
He got home to find someone sitting in 
the armchair on the left of the fireplace.

2633
03:46:22,040 --> 03:46:25,840
'Hello, Poirot,' said Mr Entwhistle.

